#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "NumPy 1.25.0 Release Notes"
msgstr "NumPy 1.25.0 發行備註"

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:7
msgid ""
"The NumPy 1.25.0 release continues the ongoing work to improve the handling "
"and promotion of dtypes, increase the execution speed, and clarify the "
"documentation. There has also been work to prepare for the future NumPy "
"2.0.0 release, resulting in a large number of new and expired deprecation. "
"Highlights are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:13
msgid "Support for MUSL, there are now MUSL wheels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:14
msgid "Support the Fujitsu C/C++ compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:15
msgid "Object arrays are now supported in einsum"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:16
msgid "Support for inplace matrix multiplication (``@=``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:18
msgid ""
"We will be releasing a NumPy 1.26 when Python 3.12 comes out. That is needed "
"because distutils has been dropped by Python 3.12 and we will be switching "
"to using meson for future builds. The next mainline release will be NumPy "
"2.0.0. We plan that the 2.0 series will still support downstream projects "
"built against earlier versions of NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:24
msgid "The Python versions supported in this release are 3.9-3.11."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:28
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:30
msgid ""
"``np.core.MachAr`` is deprecated.  It is private API.  In names defined in "
"``np.core`` should generally be considered private."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:33 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:112
msgid "(`gh-22638 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22638>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:35
msgid "``np.finfo(None)`` is deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:37
msgid "(`gh-23011 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23011>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:39
msgid "``np.round_`` is deprecated. Use `np.round` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:41
msgid "(`gh-23302 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23302>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:43
msgid "``np.product`` is deprecated. Use `np.prod` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:45 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:49
#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:53 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:57
msgid "(`gh-23314 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23314>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:47
msgid "``np.cumproduct`` is deprecated. Use `np.cumprod` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:51
msgid "``np.sometrue`` is deprecated. Use `np.any` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:55
msgid "``np.alltrue`` is deprecated. Use `np.all` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:59
msgid ""
"Only ndim-0 arrays are treated as scalars.  NumPy used to treat all arrays "
"of size 1 (e.g., ``np.array([3.14])``) as scalars.  In the future, this will "
"be limited to arrays of ndim 0 (e.g., ``np.array(3.14)``).  The following "
"expressions will report a deprecation warning:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:64
msgid ""
"a = np.array([3.14])\n"
"float(a)  # better: a[0] to get the numpy.float or a.item()\n"
"\n"
"b = np.array([[3.14]])\n"
"c = numpy.random.rand(10)\n"
"c[0] = b  # better: c[0] = b[0, 0]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:73
msgid "(`gh-10615 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/10615>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:75
msgid ""
"``np.find_common_type`` is deprecated. `numpy.find_common_type` is now "
"deprecated and its use should be replaced with either `numpy.result_type` or "
"`numpy.promote_types`. Most users leave the second ``scalar_types`` argument "
"to ``find_common_type`` as ``[]`` in which case ``np.result_type`` and ``np."
"promote_types`` are both faster and more robust. When not using "
"``scalar_types`` the main difference is that the replacement intentionally "
"converts non-native byte-order to native byte order. Further, "
"``find_common_type`` returns ``object`` dtype rather than failing "
"promotion.  This leads to differences when the inputs are not all numeric. "
"Importantly, this also happens for e.g. timedelta/datetime for which NumPy "
"promotion rules are currently sometimes surprising."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:88
msgid ""
"When the ``scalar_types`` argument is not ``[]`` things are more "
"complicated. In most cases, using ``np.result_type`` and passing the Python "
"values ``0``, ``0.0``, or ``0j`` has the same result as using ``int``, "
"``float``, or ``complex`` in `scalar_types`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:93
msgid ""
"When ``scalar_types`` is constructed, ``np.result_type`` is the correct "
"replacement and it may be passed scalar values like ``np.float32(0.0)``. "
"Passing values other than 0, may lead to value-inspecting behavior (which "
"``np.find_common_type`` never used and NEP 50 may change in the future). The "
"main possible change in behavior in this case, is when the array types are "
"signed integers and scalar types are unsigned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:100
msgid ""
"If you are unsure about how to replace a use of ``scalar_types`` or when non-"
"numeric dtypes are likely, please do not hesitate to open a NumPy issue to "
"ask for help."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:104 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:635
msgid "(`gh-22539 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22539>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:108
msgid "Expired deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:110
msgid "``np.core.machar`` and ``np.finfo.machar`` have been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:114
msgid ""
"``+arr`` will now raise an error when the dtype is not numeric (and positive "
"is undefined)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:117
msgid "(`gh-22998 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22998>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:119
msgid ""
"A sequence must now be passed into the stacking family of functions "
"(``stack``, ``vstack``, ``hstack``, ``dstack`` and ``column_stack``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:122
msgid "(`gh-23019 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23019>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:124
msgid ""
"``np.clip`` now defaults to same-kind casting. Falling back to unsafe "
"casting was deprecated in NumPy 1.17."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:127 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:132
msgid "(`gh-23403 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23403>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:129
msgid ""
"``np.clip`` will now propagate ``np.nan`` values passed as ``min`` or "
"``max``. Previously, a scalar NaN was usually ignored.  This was deprecated "
"in NumPy 1.17."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:134
msgid "The ``np.dual`` submodule has been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:136
msgid "(`gh-23480 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23480>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:138
msgid ""
"NumPy now always ignores sequence behavior for an array-like (defining one "
"of the array protocols).  (Deprecation started NumPy 1.20)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:141
msgid "(`gh-23660 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23660>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:143
msgid ""
"The niche ``FutureWarning`` when casting to a subarray dtype in ``astype`` "
"or the array creation functions such as ``asarray`` is now finalized. The "
"behavior is now always the same as if the subarray dtype was wrapped into a "
"single field (which was the workaround, previously). (FutureWarning since "
"NumPy 1.20)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:149
msgid "(`gh-23666 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23666>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:151
msgid ""
"``==`` and ``!=`` warnings have been finalized.  The ``==`` and ``!=`` "
"operators on arrays now always:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:154
msgid ""
"raise errors that occur during comparisons such as when the arrays have "
"incompatible shapes (``np.array([1, 2]) == np.array([1, 2, 3])``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:156
msgid ""
"return an array of all ``True`` or all ``False`` when values are "
"fundamentally not comparable (e.g. have different dtypes).  An example is "
"``np.array([\"a\"]) == np.array([1])``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:160
msgid ""
"This mimics the Python behavior of returning ``False`` and ``True`` when "
"comparing incompatible types like ``\"a\" == 1`` and ``\"a\" != 1``. For a "
"long time these gave ``DeprecationWarning`` or ``FutureWarning``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:164 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:227
#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:437
msgid "(`gh-22707 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22707>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:166
msgid ""
"Nose support has been removed. NumPy switched to using pytest in 2018 and "
"nose has been unmaintained for many years. We have kept NumPy's nose support "
"to avoid breaking downstream projects who might have been using it and not "
"yet switched to pytest or some other testing framework. With the arrival of "
"Python 3.12, unpatched nose will raise an error. It is time to move on."
msgstr ""

