#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:194
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.testing.utils`` shim has been removed.  Importing from the "
"``numpy.testing.utils`` shim has been deprecated since 2019, the shim has "
"now been removed. All imports should be made directly from ``numpy.testing``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:198
msgid "(`gh-23060 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23060>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:200
msgid ""
"The environment variable to disable dispatching has been removed. Support "
"for the ``NUMPY_EXPERIMENTAL_ARRAY_FUNCTION`` environment variable has been "
"removed. This variable disabled dispatching with ``__array_function__``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:204 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:210
msgid "(`gh-23376 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23376>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:206
msgid ""
"Support for ``y=`` as an alias of ``out=`` has been removed. The ``fix``, "
"``isposinf`` and ``isneginf`` functions allowed using ``y=`` as a "
"(deprecated) alias for ``out=``. This is no longer supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:214
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:216
msgid ""
"The ``busday_count`` method now correctly handles cases where the "
"``begindates`` is later in time than the ``enddates``. Previously, the "
"``enddates`` was included, even though the documentation states it is always "
"excluded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:220
msgid "(`gh-23229 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23229>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:222
msgid ""
"When comparing datetimes and timedelta using ``np.equal`` or ``np."
"not_equal`` numpy previously allowed the comparison with "
"``casting=\"unsafe\"``. This operation now fails. Forcing the output dtype "
"using the ``dtype`` kwarg can make the operation succeed, but we do not "
"recommend it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:229
msgid ""
"When loading data from a file handle using ``np.load``, if the handle is at "
"the end of file, as can happen when reading multiple arrays by calling ``np."
"load`` repeatedly, numpy previously raised ``ValueError`` if "
"``allow_pickle=False``, and ``OSError`` if ``allow_pickle=True``. Now it "
"raises ``EOFError`` instead, in both cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:235
msgid "(`gh-23105 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23105>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:238
msgid ""
"``np.pad`` with ``mode=wrap`` pads with strict multiples of original data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:239
msgid ""
"Code based on earlier version of ``pad`` that uses  ``mode=\"wrap\"`` will "
"return different results when the padding size is larger than initial array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:242
msgid ""
"``np.pad`` with ``mode=wrap`` now always fills the space with strict "
"multiples of original data even if the padding size is larger than the "
"initial array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:246
msgid "(`gh-22575 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22575>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:249
msgid "Cython ``long_t`` and ``ulong_t`` removed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:250
msgid ""
"``long_t`` and ``ulong_t`` were aliases for ``longlong_t`` and "
"``ulonglong_t`` and confusing (a remainder from of Python 2).  This change "
"may lead to the errors::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:253
msgid ""
"'long_t' is not a type identifier\n"
"'ulong_t' is not a type identifier"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:256
msgid ""
"We recommend use of bit-sized types such as ``cnp.int64_t`` or the use of "
"``cnp.intp_t`` which is 32 bits on 32 bit systems and 64 bits on 64 bit "
"systems (this is most compatible with indexing). If C ``long`` is desired, "
"use plain ``long`` or ``npy_long``. ``cnp.int_t`` is also ``long`` (NumPy's "
"default integer).  However, ``long`` is 32 bit on 64 bit windows and we may "
"wish to adjust this even in NumPy. (Please do not hesitate to contact NumPy "
"developers if you are curious about this.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:264
msgid "(`gh-22637 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22637>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:267
msgid "Changed error message and type for bad ``axes`` argument to ``ufunc``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:268
msgid ""
"The error message and type when a wrong ``axes`` value is passed to "
"``ufunc(..., axes=[...])``` has changed. The message is now more indicative "
"of the problem, and if the value is mismatched an ``AxisError`` will be "
"raised. A ``TypeError`` will still be raised for invalid input types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:273
msgid "(`gh-22675 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22675>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:276
msgid ""
"Array-likes that define ``__array_ufunc__`` can now override ufuncs if used "
"as ``where``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:277
msgid ""
"If the ``where`` keyword argument of a :class:`numpy.ufunc` is a subclass "
"of :class:`numpy.ndarray` or is a duck type that defines :func:`numpy.class."
"__array_ufunc__` it can override the behavior of the ufunc using the same "
"mechanism as the input and output arguments. Note that for this to work "
"properly, the ``where.__array_ufunc__`` implementation will have to unwrap "
"the ``where`` argument to pass it into the default implementation of the "
"``ufunc`` or, for :class:`numpy.ndarray` subclasses before using ``super()."
"__array_ufunc__``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:286
msgid "(`gh-23240 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23240>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:289
msgid ""
"Compiling against the NumPy C API is now backwards compatible by default"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:290
msgid ""
"NumPy now defaults to exposing a backwards compatible subset of the C-API. "
"This makes the use of ``oldest-supported-numpy`` unnecessary. Libraries can "
"override the default minimal version to be compatible with using::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:295
msgid "#define NPY_TARGET_VERSION NPY_1_22_API_VERSION"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:297
msgid ""
"before including NumPy or by passing the equivalent ``-D`` option to the "
"compiler. The NumPy 1.25 default is ``NPY_1_19_API_VERSION``.  Because the "
"NumPy 1.19 C API was identical to the NumPy 1.16 one resulting programs will "
"be compatible with NumPy 1.16 (from a C-API perspective). This default will "
"be increased in future non-bugfix releases. You can still compile against an "
"older NumPy version and run on a newer one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:305
msgid "For more details please see :ref:`for-downstream-package-authors`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:307
msgid "(`gh-23528 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23528>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:311
msgid "New Features"
msgstr "新功能"

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:314
msgid "``np.einsum`` now accepts arrays with ``object`` dtype"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:315
msgid ""
"The code path will call python operators on object dtype arrays, much like "
"``np.dot`` and ``np.matmul``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:318
msgid "(`gh-18053 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/18053>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:321
msgid "Add support for inplace matrix multiplication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:322
msgid ""
"It is now possible to perform inplace matrix multiplication via the ``@=`` "
"operator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:325
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np\n"
"\n"
">>> a = np.arange(6).reshape(3, 2)\n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[[0 1]\n"
" [2 3]\n"
" [4 5]]\n"
"\n"
">>> b = np.ones((2, 2), dtype=int)\n"
">>> a @= b\n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[[1 1]\n"
" [5 5]\n"
" [9 9]]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:342
msgid "(`gh-21120 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21120>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:345
msgid "Added ``NPY_ENABLE_CPU_FEATURES`` environment variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:346
msgid ""
"Users may now choose to enable only a subset of the built CPU features at "
"runtime by specifying the `NPY_ENABLE_CPU_FEATURES` environment variable. "
"Note that these specified features must be outside the baseline, since those "
"are always assumed. Errors will be raised if attempting to enable a feature "
"that is either not supported by your CPU, or that NumPy was not built with."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:352
msgid "(`gh-22137 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22137>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:355
msgid "NumPy now has an ``np.exceptions`` namespace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:356
msgid ""
"NumPy now has a dedicated namespace making most exceptions and warnings "
"available.  All of these remain available in the main namespace, although "
"some may be moved slowly in the future. The main reason for this is to "
"increase discoverability and add future exceptions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:362
msgid "(`gh-22644 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22644>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:365
msgid "``np.linalg`` functions return NamedTuples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:366
msgid ""
"``np.linalg`` functions that return tuples now return namedtuples. These "
"functions are ``eig()``, ``eigh()``, ``qr()``, ``slogdet()``, and ``svd()``. "
"The return type is unchanged in instances where these functions return non-"
"tuples with certain keyword arguments (like ``svd(compute_uv=False)``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:371
msgid "(`gh-22786 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22786>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:374
msgid ""
"String functions in ``np.char`` are compatible with NEP 42 custom dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:375
msgid ""
"Custom dtypes that represent unicode strings or byte strings can now be "
"passed to the string functions in ``np.char``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:378
msgid "(`gh-22863 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22863>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:381
msgid ""
"String dtype instances can be created from the string abstract dtype classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:382
msgid ""
"It is now possible to create a string dtype instance with a size without "
"using the string name of the dtype. For example, ``type(np.dtype('U'))(8)`` "
"will create a dtype that is equivalent to ``np.dtype('U8')``. This feature "
"is most useful when writing generic code dealing with string dtype classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:388
msgid "(`gh-22963 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22963>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:391
msgid "Fujitsu C/C++ compiler is now supported"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:392
msgid ""
"Support for Fujitsu compiler has been added. To build with Fujitsu compiler, "
"run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:395
msgid "python setup.py build -c fujitsu"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:399
msgid "SSL2 is now supported"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:400
msgid ""
"Support for SSL2 has been added. SSL2 is a library that provides OpenBLAS "
"compatible GEMM functions.  To enable SSL2, it need to edit site.cfg and "
"build with Fujitsu compiler.  See site.cfg.example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:404
msgid "(`gh-22982 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22982>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:408
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:411
msgid "``NDArrayOperatorsMixin`` specifies that it has no ``__slots__``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:412
msgid ""
"The ``NDArrayOperatorsMixin`` class now specifies that it contains no "
"``__slots__``, ensuring that subclasses can now make use of this feature in "
"Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:416
msgid "(`gh-23113 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23113>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:419
msgid "Fix power of complex zero"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:420
msgid ""
"``np.power`` now returns a different result for ``0^{non-zero}`` for complex "
"numbers.  Note that the value is only defined when the real part of the "
"exponent is larger than zero. Previously, NaN was returned unless the "
"imaginary part was strictly zero.  The return value is either ``0+0j`` or "
"``0-0j``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:426
msgid "(`gh-18535 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/18535>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:429
msgid "New ``DTypePromotionError``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:430
msgid ""
"NumPy now has a new ``DTypePromotionError`` which is used when two dtypes "
"cannot be promoted to a common one, for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:433
msgid "np.result_type(\"M8[s]\", np.complex128)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:435
msgid "raises this new exception."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:440
msgid "`np.show_config` uses information from Meson"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:441
msgid ""
"Build and system information now contains information from Meson. `np."
"show_config` now has a new optional parameter ``mode`` to help customize the "
"output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:445
msgid "(`gh-22769 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22769>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:448
msgid ""
"Fix ``np.ma.diff`` not preserving the mask when called with arguments "
"prepend/append."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:449
msgid ""
"Calling ``np.ma.diff`` with arguments prepend and/or append now returns a "
"``MaskedArray`` with the input mask preserved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:452
msgid "Previously, a ``MaskedArray`` without the mask was returned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:454
msgid "(`gh-22776 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22776>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:457
msgid "Corrected error handling for NumPy C-API in Cython"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:458
msgid ""
"Many NumPy C functions defined for use in Cython were lacking the correct "
"error indicator like ``except -1`` or ``except *``. These have now been "
"added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:462
msgid "(`gh-22997 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22997>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:465
msgid "Ability to directly spawn random number generators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:466
msgid ""
"`numpy.random.Generator.spawn` now allows to directly spawn new independent "
"child generators via the `numpy.random.SeedSequence.spawn` mechanism. `numpy."
"random.BitGenerator.spawn` does the same for the underlying bit generator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:472
msgid ""
"Additionally, `numpy.random.BitGenerator.seed_seq` now gives direct access "
"to the seed sequence used for initializing the bit generator. This allows "
"for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:476
msgid ""
"seed = 0x2e09b90939db40c400f8f22dae617151\n"
"rng = np.random.default_rng(seed)\n"
"child_rng1, child_rng2 = rng.spawn(2)\n"
"\n"
"# safely use rng, child_rng1, and child_rng2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:482
msgid ""
"Previously, this was hard to do without passing the ``SeedSequence`` "
"explicitly.  Please see `numpy.random.SeedSequence` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:485
msgid "(`gh-23195 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23195>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:488
msgid "``numpy.logspace`` now supports a non-scalar ``base`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:489
msgid ""
"The ``base`` argument of ``numpy.logspace`` can now be array-like if it is "
"broadcastable against the ``start`` and ``stop`` arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:492
msgid "(`gh-23275 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23275>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:495
msgid "``np.ma.dot()`` now supports for non-2d arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:496
msgid ""
"Previously ``np.ma.dot()`` only worked if ``a`` and ``b`` were both 2d. Now "
"it works for non-2d arrays as well as ``np.dot()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:499
msgid "(`gh-23322 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23322>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:502
msgid "Explicitly show keys of .npz file in repr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:503
msgid "``NpzFile`` shows keys of loaded .npz file when printed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:505
msgid ""
">>> npzfile = np.load('arr.npz')\n"
">>> npzfile\n"
"NpzFile 'arr.npz' with keys arr_0, arr_1, arr_2, arr_3, arr_4..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:511
msgid "(`gh-23357 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23357>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:514
msgid "NumPy now exposes DType classes in ``np.dtypes``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:515
msgid ""
"The new ``numpy.dtypes`` module now exposes DType classes and will contain "
"future dtype related functionality. Most users should have no need to use "
"these classes directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:519
msgid "(`gh-23358 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23358>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:522
msgid "Drop dtype metadata before saving in .npy or .npz files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:523
msgid ""
"Currently, a ``*.npy`` file containing a table with a dtype with metadata "
"cannot be read back. Now, `np.save` and `np.savez` drop metadata before "
"saving."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:527
msgid "(`gh-23371 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23371>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:530
msgid ""
"``numpy.lib.recfunctions.structured_to_unstructured`` returns views in more "
"cases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:531
msgid ""
"``structured_to_unstructured`` now returns a view, if the stride between the "
"fields is constant. Prior, padding between the fields or a reversed field "
"would lead to a copy. This change only applies to ``ndarray``, ``memmap`` "
"and ``recarray``. For all other array subclasses, the behavior remains "
"unchanged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:537
msgid "(`gh-23652 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23652>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:540
msgid "Signed and unsigned integers always compare correctly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:541
msgid ""
"When ``uint64`` and ``int64`` are mixed in NumPy, NumPy typically promotes "
"both to ``float64``.  This behavior may be argued about but is confusing for "
"comparisons ``==``, ``<=``, since the results returned can be incorrect but "
"the conversion is hidden since the result is a boolean. NumPy will now "
"return the correct results for these by avoiding the cast to float."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:549
msgid "(`gh-23713 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23713>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:553
msgid "Performance improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:556
msgid "Faster ``np.argsort`` on AVX-512 enabled processors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:557
msgid ""
"32-bit and 64-bit quicksort algorithm for np.argsort gain up to 6x speed up "
"on processors that support AVX-512 instruction set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:560 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:570
msgid ""
"Thanks to `Intel corporation <https://open.intel.com/>`_ for sponsoring this "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:563
msgid "(`gh-23707 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23707>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:566
msgid "Faster ``np.sort`` on AVX-512 enabled processors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:567
msgid ""
"Quicksort for 16-bit and 64-bit dtypes gain up to 15x and 9x speed up on "
"processors that support AVX-512 instruction set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:573
msgid "(`gh-22315 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/22315>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:576
msgid "``__array_function__`` machinery is now much faster"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:577
msgid ""
"The overhead of the majority of functions in NumPy is now smaller especially "
"when keyword arguments are used.  This change significantly speeds up many "
"simple function calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:581 ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:647
msgid "(`gh-23020 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23020>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:584
msgid "``ufunc.at`` can be much faster"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:585
msgid ""
"Generic ``ufunc.at`` can be up to 9x faster. The conditions for this speedup:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:587
msgid "operands are aligned"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:588
msgid "no casting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:590
msgid ""
"If ufuncs with appropriate indexed loops on 1d arguments with the above "
"conditions, ``ufunc.at`` can be up to 60x faster (an additional 7x speedup). "
"Appropriate indexed loops have been added to ``add``, ``subtract``, "
"``multiply``, ``floor_divide``, ``maximum``, ``minimum``, ``fmax``, and "
"``fmin``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:596
msgid ""
"The internal logic is similar to the logic used for regular ufuncs, which "
"also have fast paths."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:599
msgid ""
"Thanks to the `D. E. Shaw group <https://deshaw.com/>`_ for sponsoring this "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:602
msgid "(`gh-23136 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23136>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:605
msgid "Faster membership test on ``NpzFile``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:606
msgid ""
"Membership test on ``NpzFile`` will no longer decompress the archive if it "
"is successful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:609
msgid "(`gh-23661 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23661>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:613
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:616
msgid "``np.r_[]`` and ``np.c_[]`` with certain scalar values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:617
msgid ""
"In rare cases, using mainly ``np.r_`` with scalars can lead to different "
"results.  The main potential changes are highlighted by the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:620
msgid ""
">>> np.r_[np.arange(5, dtype=np.uint8), -1].dtype\n"
"int16  # rather than the default integer (int64 or int32)\n"
">>> np.r_[np.arange(5, dtype=np.int8), 255]\n"
"array([  0,   1,   2,   3,   4, 255], dtype=int16)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:625
msgid "Where the second example returned::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:627
msgid "array([ 0,  1,  2,  3,  4, -1], dtype=int8)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:629
msgid ""
"The first one is due to a signed integer scalar with an unsigned integer "
"array, while the second is due to ``255`` not fitting into ``int8`` and "
"NumPy currently inspecting values to make this work. (Note that the second "
"example is expected to change in the future due to :ref:`NEP 50 <NEP50>`; it "
"will then raise an error.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:638
msgid "Most NumPy functions are wrapped into a C-callable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:639
msgid ""
"To speed up the ``__array_function__`` dispatching, most NumPy functions are "
"now wrapped into C-callables and are not proper Python functions or C "
"methods. They still look and feel the same as before (like a Python "
"function), and this should only improve performance and user experience "
"(cleaner tracebacks). However, please inform the NumPy developers if this "
"change confuses your program for some reason."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:650
msgid "C++ standard library usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:651
msgid ""
"NumPy builds now depend on the C++ standard library, because the ``numpy."
"core._multiarray_umath`` extension is linked with the C++ linker."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.25.0-notes.rst:655
msgid "(`gh-23601 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/23601>`__)"
msgstr ""
